<subSubSection id="C37F6512FF91FFECFF4C2993C5402F50" pageId="12" pageNumber="333" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="8BDA3699FF91FFECFF4C2993C5402F50" blockId="12.[151,1437,356,1136]" pageId="12" pageNumber="333">
<emphasis id="B911EA8BFF91FFECFF4C2993C7232CA5" bold="true" box="[199,321,428,453]" pageId="12" pageNumber="333">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
Shiny appearance, poorly pubescent, long rostrum, as long as the sum of antennomeres I+II, body small when compared with other 
<taxonomicName id="4C654D1AFF91FFECFD8629EFC4852C88" box="[525,743,464,488]" class="Insecta" family="Lycidae" genus="Macrolygistopterus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="12" pageNumber="333" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B911EA8BFF91FFECFD8629EFC4852C88" box="[525,743,464,488]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="333">Macrolygistopterus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species, costae I and IV apically fused, forming an arch, with elytral 
<number id="3DAD24BEFF91FFECFF6D29CBC6962F6D" box="[230,244,500,525]" pageId="12" pageNumber="333" value="4.0">4</number>
/ 
<number id="3DAD24BEFF91FFECFF7529CBC7692F6D" box="[254,267,500,525]" pageId="12" pageNumber="333" value="5.0">5</number>
strongly obliterated; costa III obliterated at elytral 
<number id="3DAD24BEFF91FFECFCDB29CBC53D2F6D" box="[848,863,500,525]" pageId="12" pageNumber="333" value="4.0">4</number>
/ 
<number id="3DAD24BEFF91FFECFCE229CBC5152F6D" box="[873,887,500,525]" pageId="12" pageNumber="333" value="5.0">5</number>
; costa II reaching elytral apex, crossing the arch formed by costae I+IV, obliterated after the arch (
<figureCitation id="135E2A1CFF91FFECFD4A2A28C5742F50" box="[705,790,535,560]" captionStart="FIGURES 27 – 35" captionStartId="7.[151,264,1714,1737]" captionTargetBox="[156,1429,204,1685]" captionTargetId="figure@7.[151,1436,195,1693]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURES 27 – 35. Elytra: 27. Macrolygistopterus succinctus; 28. M. quadricostatus; 29. M. caeruleus; 30. M. germaini; 31. M. grandjeani; 32. M. subparallelus; 33. M. testaceirostris; 34. M. simoni; 35. M. kirschi Scale bar 1 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/271310/files/figure.png" pageId="12" pageNumber="333">
Fig. 
<number id="3DAD24BEFF91FFECFD7D2A27C5742F50" box="[758,790,536,560]" pageId="12" pageNumber="333" value="34.0">34</number>
</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C37F6512FF91FFECFF4C2A03C5732965" pageId="12" pageNumber="333" type="description">
<paragraph id="8BDA3699FF91FFECFF4C2A03C7BB2F85" blockId="12.[151,1437,356,1136]" pageId="12" pageNumber="333">
<emphasis id="B911EA8BFF91FFECFF4C2A03C7162F35" bold="true" box="[199,372,572,597]" pageId="12" pageNumber="333">Redescription.</emphasis>
Head black, prolonged in a long rostrum, as long as the sum of antennomeres I+II (
<figureCitation id="135E2A1CFF91FFECFAB22A03C3EC2F34" box="[1337,1422,572,597]" captionStart="FIGURES 10 – 18" captionStartId="5.[151,264,1433,1456]" captionTargetBox="[156,1432,198,1400]" captionTargetId="figure@5.[151,1435,193,1413]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURES 10 – 18. Rostrum: 10. Macrolygistopterus succinctus; 11. M. quadricostatus; 12. M. caeruleus; 13. M. germaini; 14. M. grandjeani; 15. M. subparallelus; 16. M. testaceirostris; 17. M. simoni; 18. M. kirschi. Scale bar 1 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/271308/files/figure.png" pageId="12" pageNumber="333">
Fig. 
<number id="3DAD24BEFF91FFECFAE42A03C3EC2F34" box="[1391,1422,572,596]" pageId="12" pageNumber="333" value="17.0">17</number>
</figureCitation>
); median interocular distance of 
<date id="FFDB1059FF91FFECFD982A5FC44C2F18" box="[531,558,608,632]" pageId="12" pageNumber="333">
<number id="3DAD24BEFF91FFECFD982A5FC4432F18" box="[531,545,608,632]" pageId="12" pageNumber="333" value="2.0">2</number>
x
</date>
eye width. Mandibles simple, not curved, slightly shorter than labrum, testaceous. Maxillary palp with palpomere I short, about 
<number id="3DAD24BEFF91FFECFC9C2ABBC5432FFC" box="[791,801,644,668]" pageId="12" pageNumber="333" value="1.0">1</number>
/ 
<number id="3DAD24BEFF91FFECFCA62ABBC5592FFC" box="[813,827,644,668]" pageId="12" pageNumber="333" value="3.0">3</number>
the length of II; palpomere II subconic, as long as III; palpomere IV truncated, transverse, securiform. Antennae with scape conic; pedicel with 
<number id="3DAD24BEFF91FFECFB2E2A98C2CD2FA0" box="[1189,1199,679,704]" pageId="12" pageNumber="333" value="1.0">1</number>
/ 
<number id="3DAD24BEFF91FFECFB312A98C2AB2FA0" box="[1210,1225,679,704]" pageId="12" pageNumber="333" value="5.0">5</number>
of scape’s length, other antennomeres missing.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BDA3699FF91FFECFF4C2ACFC2622E30" blockId="12.[151,1437,356,1136]" pageId="12" pageNumber="333">
Pronotum pentagonal, wider than longer (
<number id="3DAD24BEFF91FFECFD232AD0C4D52E68" box="[680,695,751,776]" pageId="12" pageNumber="333" value="6.0">6</number>
: 
<number id="3DAD24BEFF91FFECFD302AD0C4862E68" box="[699,740,751,776]" pageId="12" pageNumber="333" value="7.5">7,5</number>
), rounded angles, testaceous, with a wide longitudinal black strip; a pair of median elevations widened in median third; a pair of weak oblique elevations in median and basal region (
<figureCitation id="135E2A1CFF91FFECFF652B08C7202E30" box="[238,322,823,848]" captionStart="FIGURES 19 – 26" captionStartId="6.[151,264,1260,1283]" captionTargetBox="[158,1430,200,1229]" captionTargetId="figure@6.[150,1436,193,1239]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURES 19 – 26. Pronotum: 19. Macrolygistopterus succinctus; 20. M. quadricostatus; 21. M. caeruleus; 22. M. germaini; 23. M. grandjeani; 24. M. simoni; 25. M. subparallelus; 26. M. testaceirostris. Scale bar 1 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/271309/files/figure.png" pageId="12" pageNumber="333">
Fig. 
<number id="3DAD24BEFF91FFECFEA92B07C7202E30" box="[290,322,824,848]" pageId="12" pageNumber="333" value="24.0">24</number>
